ACM (AWS Certificate Manager) has one main job:
Manage SSL/TLS certificates for your domain.

SSL is the name, TLS is the technology — everyone uses SSL because it was first and the name stuck!

SSL  =  old name, deprecated protocol
TLS  =  new name, current protocol

But in conversation:
  SSL = TLS = same meaning ✅
  nobody will correct you
  even engineers say SSL
  even AWS says SSL
  
Just remember:
  technically  →  TLS is correct
  practically  →  SSL and TLS mean same thing

------------------
Even AWS mixes the terms:

AWS Console says:
  "SSL/TLS certificate"   ← uses both together
  "SSL policy"            ← actually means TLS policy
  "SSL termination"       ← actually means TLS termination

Because they know people say SSL
even though TLS is what actually runs

Same thing, different name:

SSL certificate    =    TLS certificate
SSL termination    =    TLS termination
SSL handshake      =    TLS handshake
SSL port 443       =    TLS port 443
HTTPS              =    HTTP over TLS
                        (not HTTP over SSL anymore)

What SSL certificate actually does:

Without SSL:
  browser shows ❌ Not Secure
  http://accessmyiq.com
  all data travels unencrypted
  anyone can read it 😱

With SSL:
  browser shows 🔒 padlock
  https://accessmyiq.com
  all data encrypted
  safe from hackers ✅
------------------
Where ACM certificates attach:

ACM Certificate
  ├── CloudFront    ✅ global CDN
  ├── ALB           ✅ load balancer
  ├── API Gateway   ✅ APIs
  └── NLB           ❌ does not support ACM
                       (NLB is Layer 4, no SSL)

Simple summary:

ACM = free SSL certificate manager

Gives you:
  ✅ FREE certificate
  ✅ auto renewal
  ✅ easy setup
  ✅ attaches to ALB, CloudFront, API Gateway

Does NOT give you:
  ❌ CDN (that is CloudFront)
  ❌ WAF (that is AWS WAF)
  ❌ DDoS (that is AWS Shield)
  ❌ works with NLB (Layer 4, no SSL support)
---------------------------
NLB supports TLS at Layer 4:

NLB TLS support:
  ✅ TLS passthrough   → forwards encrypted traffic as is
  ✅ TLS termination   → NLB decrypts, forwards plain HTTP

Two modes NLB handles TLS:
Mode 1 — TLS Passthrough (what your company uses)

User
  ↓ HTTPS/TLS encrypted
NLB
  ↓ forwards encrypted packets AS IS
  ↓ does NOT decrypt
  ↓ does NOT need certificate
NGINX
  ↓ decrypts here (or Akamai already did)
Pods

Mode 2 — TLS Termination at NLB

User
  ↓ HTTPS/TLS encrypted
NLB
  ↓ decrypts here ✅
  ↓ needs ACM certificate ✅
  ↓ forwards plain TCP
NGINX
  ↓ receives plain HTTP
Pods

NLB DOES support ACM:

NLB + TLS termination:
  ✅ attach ACM certificate to NLB
  ✅ NLB decrypts TLS
  ✅ forwards plain traffic to NGINX

BUT only for TCP listener
not HTTP/HTTPS listener

Simple summary:

NLB TLS support:
  ✅ TLS passthrough    (forwards encrypted as is)
  ✅ TLS termination    (decrypts, needs ACM cert)
  ✅ ACM certificate    (when terminating TLS)
  ❌ HTTP routing       (still needs NGINX for that)

My earlier statement was wrong!
NLB does support TLS and ACM ✅


Simple summary:

Both NLB and ALB:
  ✅ SSL/TLS certificate
  ✅ SSL/TLS termination
  ✅ SSL/TLS handshake
  ✅ TLS 1.2 and 1.3
  ✅ ACM certificates

Only NLB:
  ✅ TLS passthrough

Only ALB:
  ✅ HTTP routing after TLS
  ✅ full SSL policy control

Both support all SSL/TLS features — NLB just adds passthrough and ALB adds HTTP routing on top!

Full comparison table:

Feature                     | ALB        | NLB
---------------------------|------------|------------
ACM certificate            | Yes        | Yes
TLS termination            | Yes        | Yes
TLS passthrough            | No         | Yes
TLS handshake              | Yes        | Yes
TLS 1.2                    | Yes        | Yes
TLS 1.3                    | Yes        | Yes
SSL policy control         | Full       | Limited
SNI support                | Yes        | Yes
HTTP routing after TLS     | Yes        | No (needs NGINX)
Multiple certificates      | Yes        | Yes

SSL/TLS Termination:

ALB:
  ✅ terminates TLS
  ✅ decrypts at Layer 7
  ✅ reads HTTP after decryption
  ✅ routes based on path/host

NLB:
  ✅ terminates TLS
  ✅ decrypts at Layer 4
  ❌ cannot read HTTP after decryption
  ❌ cannot route based on path/host
  needs NGINX for routing

SSL/TLS Handshake:

ALB:
  ✅ handles TLS handshake
  ✅ TLS 1.2 supported
  ✅ TLS 1.3 supported
  ✅ full SSL policy control
     (choose exact ciphers)

NLB:
  ✅ handles TLS handshake
  ✅ TLS 1.2 supported
  ✅ TLS 1.3 supported
  ⚠️ limited SSL policy options
     (fewer cipher choices than ALB)

TLS Passthrough — only NLB:

NLB only:
  ✅ TLS passthrough
     forwards encrypted traffic
     without decrypting
     NGINX or app decrypts

ALB:
  ❌ no TLS passthrough
     ALB always terminates TLS
     cannot forward encrypted traffic














